\section{Design Solution}\label{design-solution}

\subsection{Problem Definition}\label{problem-definition}

\subsubsection{Background: UWB Positioning and the NLOS
Challenge}\label{background-uwb-positioning-and-the-nlos-challenge}

Ultra-Wideband (UWB) radio technology is widely used for high-precision
indoor positioning because its large bandwidth enables fine
time-of-arrival (ToA) measurements with sub-nanosecond temporal
resolution {[}1{]}. Under ideal conditions, this supports very accurate
ranging and has made UWB attractive for applications such as industrial
asset tracking, hospital monitoring, autonomous robotic navigation, and
consumer-device localization {[}1{]}, {[}2{]}.

However, the accuracy of UWB positioning degrades severely in real
indoor environments due to \textbf{Non-Line-of-Sight (NLOS) propagation}
{[}2{]}--{[}4{]}. When the direct radio path between a transmitter and
receiver is obstructed by walls, furniture, or the human body, the
measured time-of-arrival no longer corresponds to the true direct-path
distance. Instead, the first detected signal has traveled a longer,
reflected or diffracted path, introducing a \textbf{positive ranging
bias} that can be several meters {[}3{]}, {[}4{]}. This systematic
error, unlike random noise, which can be averaged out, cannot be reduced
by repeated measurements and must be explicitly detected and compensated
{[}2{]}, {[}4{]}.

Global Navigation Satellite Systems (GNSS, including GPS) do not
function reliably indoors, making accurate indoor positioning a
long-standing open challenge {[}2{]}. NLOS mitigation is therefore a
critical research area for enabling robust centimeter-level indoor
positioning {[}2{]}--{[}4{]}.

\subsubsection{The Channel Impulse Response
(CIR)}\label{the-channel-impulse-response-cir}

UWB receivers such as the Decawave DWM1000 module provide access to the
\textbf{Channel Impulse Response (CIR)}, a digital snapshot of the
received radio channel measured at 1 nanosecond resolution across 1016
samples. The CIR captures the complete multipath propagation profile:
the direct path (if LOS), reflected paths from walls and objects, and
diffracted paths around obstacles. LOS and NLOS propagation leave
distinct fingerprints in the CIR shape:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{LOS CIR}: A sharp, dominant first peak arrives early, with a
  steep rise and rapid decay. The energy is concentrated around the
  first path.
\item
  \textbf{NLOS CIR}: The first-arriving component is attenuated or
  absent (blocked by an obstacle). Energy is spread across later
  multipath components with a more gradual onset. The hardware-reported
  first-path index (FP\_IDX) may not correspond to the true direct path.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Problem Statement and
Objectives}\label{problem-statement-and-objectives}

This project addresses two interrelated tasks:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \textbf{Two-Path LOS/NLOS Classification}: Given a single CIR
  measurement, extract the two dominant propagation paths and classify
  each as LOS or NLOS. This extends the standard binary classification
  problem to a per-path labeling task, reflecting the physical reality
  that each CIR contains multiple propagation components.
\item
  \textbf{Distance Estimation}: For each of the two extracted paths,
  estimate the physical propagation distance (in meters), enabling
  accurate position calculation even in the presence of multipath.
\end{enumerate}

The \textbf{two-path labeling rule} used in this report follows a
standard UWB propagation assumption: when an LOS component exists, it is
the earliest-arriving path. Under this assumption, if Path 1 (the
first-arriving peak) is classified as LOS, then Path 2 (the next
strongest peak) is labeled NLOS. If Path 1 is itself NLOS (direct path
blocked), then Path 2 is also labeled NLOS. In effect, Path 2 is always
labeled NLOS under this rule.

\subsubsection{Dataset}\label{dataset}

The dataset originates from Bregar and Mohorčič {[}7{]} and was
collected using Decawave DWM1000 UWB modules across \textbf{7 distinct
indoor environments} at the Jožef Stefan Institute, Slovenia. The
dataset comprises:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{42,000 measurements}: 21,000 LOS and 21,000 NLOS (perfectly
  balanced), pre-randomized across environments
\item
  \textbf{14 scalar features}: RANGE (also used as the regression target
  for distance estimation), FP\_IDX, FP\_AMP1, FP\_AMP2, FP\_AMP3,
  STDEV\_NOISE, CIR\_PWR, MAX\_NOISE, RXPACC, CH, FRAME\_LEN,
  PREAM\_LEN, BITRATE, PRFR
\item
  \textbf{1016 CIR samples}: Absolute channel impulse response
  amplitudes at 1 ns resolution (columns CIR0 through CIR1015)
\item
  \textbf{Target label}: NLOS (1 = NLOS, 0 = LOS)
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Proposed Approach}\label{proposed-approach}

We propose a \textbf{dual-pipeline architecture} that combines classical
machine learning on hand-crafted features with end-to-end deep learning
on raw CIR waveforms:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Pipeline 1 (Feature-Engineered ML)}: Extract 25
  physics-motivated features per path, then train and compare Logistic
  Regression, Random Forest, Gradient Boosted Trees (GBT), and XGBoost
  classifiers.
\item
  \textbf{Pipeline 2 (End-to-End DL)}: Feed the raw 1016-sample CIR
  directly into a hybrid CNN+Transformer architecture that learns its
  own representations.
\end{itemize}

The feature-engineered ML pipeline is evaluated on the expanded two-path
dataset, while the CNN+Transformer results are reported from a separate
pipeline that operates on raw CIR waveforms with the original train/test
split. This design supports a qualitative comparison between the two
representation strategies but does not constitute a strictly controlled
benchmark.

Classical NLOS-mitigation studies {[}2{]}--{[}4{]} describe the
propagation mechanisms that motivate our hand-crafted features, while
recent learning-based studies {[}5{]}, {[}10{]}, {[}11{]} show that
discriminative CIR representations can be learned directly from waveform
structure. Our contribution is therefore not the use of transformers in
isolation, but the integration of a hybrid CNN+Transformer model within
a broader two-path extraction framework and its comparison against a
feature-engineered ML pipeline on the Bregar and Mohorčič dataset
{[}7{]}.

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\subsection{Problem Analysis}\label{problem-analysis}

\subsubsection{The Two-Path Extension
Framework}\label{the-two-path-extension-framework}

Standard UWB LOS/NLOS classification treats each measurement as a binary
classification problem: given the CIR, predict whether the measurement
is LOS or NLOS. This project extends the problem to \textbf{per-path
classification}: identify the two most prominent peaks in the CIR and
classify each individually.

This extension requires solving three sub-problems simultaneously:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Peak Detection}: Reliably locate two dominant peaks in a noisy
  1016-sample waveform
\item
  \textbf{Feature Extraction}: Compute discriminative features for each
  detected peak independently
\item
  \textbf{Label Assignment}: Determine the correct NLOS label for each
  path using the two-path rule
\end{enumerate}

The expanded dataset has a natural \textbf{class imbalance}: after
preprocessing, 41,996 usable measurements remain, and the two-path
expansion therefore yields \textbf{83,992 rows}. Path 2 is always
labeled NLOS (1), while Path 1 inherits the original label (roughly 50\%
LOS, 50\% NLOS). The resulting expanded class distribution is 25\% LOS /
75\% NLOS. This imbalance is handled through class-weighted loss
functions in the classical ML pipeline; the deep learning results come
from a separate raw-CIR workflow on the original split and should be
interpreted separately.

\subsubsection{The 3D Analytics Process}\label{the-3d-analytics-process}

The project follows the standard data analytics pipeline:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Data Preparation}: Loading, cleaning, CIR normalization, path
  extraction, feature engineering, and augmentation analysis
\item
  \textbf{Data Mining}: Training supervised classifiers, the
  CNN+Transformer model, and unsupervised K-Means clustering; regression
  for distance estimation
\item
  \textbf{Data Visualization}: Producing 14 diagnostic plots covering
  class distributions, CIR waveforms, feature importance, confusion
  matrices, ROC curves, clustering structure, regression scatter plots,
  and transformer attention maps
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Algorithm Design
Rationale}\label{algorithm-design-rationale}

\textbf{Why hand-crafted features?} Physics-motivated features such as
rise time, kurtosis, and energy ratio encode known differences between
LOS and NLOS CIR profiles reported in prior UWB ranging and
NLOS-identification work {[}3{]}, {[}4{]}. They are interpretable,
computationally efficient, and allow incorporation of domain expertise.

\textbf{Why CNN + Transformer?} Convolutional layers capture local
waveform patterns (peak shapes, rise/decay profiles), while the
Transformer encoder captures long-range dependencies across the entire
1016-sample CIR (e.g., energy distribution between the first path and
later multipath components) {[}6{]}, {[}10{]}, {[}11{]}. This
combination is well-suited to the sequential structure of CIR data, as
demonstrated by recent transformer-based UWB NLOS detection work
{[}10{]}, {[}11{]}.

\textbf{Why K-Means clustering?} An unsupervised baseline tests whether
the engineered feature space contains LOS/NLOS structure without label
information. In the evaluated notebook run, K-Means is applied directly
to the expanded two-path 25-feature train/test matrices used by the
tabular classifiers; no additional scaling step is applied inside the
clustering module. The resulting metrics are therefore interpreted as a
weak, imbalanced-set baseline rather than a balanced Path-1-only
clustering benchmark.

\textbf{Why ensemble methods?} RF, GBT, XGBoost, and CNN+Transformer
each have complementary strengths. Averaging their predicted
probabilities reduces model-specific errors, while stacked
generalization trains a meta-learner to optimally weight each model's
contribution.

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\subsection{Algorithm and Evaluation
Criteria}\label{algorithm-and-evaluation-criteria}

\subsubsection{Two-Path Peak Detection}\label{two-path-peak-detection}

The hardware-reported FP\_IDX provides a coarse estimate of the first
path location but does not always correspond to the exact local maximum
in the CIR. Path detection proceeds as follows:

\textbf{Path 1 Detection}: A search window of ±10 samples around FP\_IDX
is extracted, and the sample with maximum amplitude within this window
is identified as the Path 1 peak. This refinement corrects for small
hardware timing errors.

\textbf{Path 2 Detection}: The raw CIR is first smoothed with a 3-sample
moving average kernel to reduce local noise fluctuations. Then
\texttt{scipy.signal.find\_peaks} is applied with:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Height threshold: 2\% of Path 1 amplitude (to reject noise floor
  peaks)
\item
  Minimum inter-peak distance: 15 samples (to avoid detecting the same
  peak twice)
\item
  Minimum prominence: 2\% of Path 1 amplitude (to ensure the peak is
  genuinely distinguishable from surrounding local maxima)
\end{itemize}

Candidate peaks within ±15 samples of Path 1 are excluded, and the
remaining candidate with the highest \textbf{prominence} (not raw
amplitude) is selected as Path 2. Prominence measures how much a peak
stands out relative to its surrounding baseline, making it more robust
than raw amplitude for identifying secondary multipath components. The
Path 2 amplitude is then read from the original (unsmoothed) CIR to
preserve accuracy.

On the preprocessed dataset, this algorithm detects Path 2 in
\textbf{40,864 of 41,996 usable samples (97.3\%)}. The remaining cases
do not contain a sufficiently distinct second peak under the chosen
prominence and separation constraints.

For samples without a valid second peak, the implementation retains the
sample and assigns \texttt{path2\_idx\ =\ 0} and
\texttt{path2\_amp\ =\ 0.0}, consistent with Algorithm 1. These rows
remain in the expanded dataset and are handled by downstream feature
engineering and modeling.

\subsubsection{Feature Engineering Pipeline (25 Features Per
Path)}\label{feature-engineering-pipeline-25-features-per-path}

\paragraph{Per-Path Waveform Features (8
features)}\label{per-path-waveform-features-8-features}

For each detected peak, a local ±15-sample window is extracted from the
CIR, and the following features are computed:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{path\_idx}}: The CIR sample index of the detected peak
  (temporal location)
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{path\_amp}}: The absolute amplitude of the peak in the
  CIR
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{rise\_time}}: The number of samples between the point
  where amplitude first exceeds 10\% of the peak value (searching
  leftward from the peak) and the peak itself. Measures how sharply the
  path arrives.
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{decay\_time}}: Symmetric to rise\_time, measuring how
  quickly amplitude decays after the peak. NLOS signals typically have
  longer, slower decays.
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{kurtosis\_local}}: Fisher kurtosis of the local
  ±15-sample window. High kurtosis indicates a sharp, spiky peak
  (typical of LOS direct paths). Low kurtosis indicates a flat,
  spread-out shape (typical of NLOS scattered paths).
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{energy\_ratio}}: Ratio of the local window's energy
  (sum of squared amplitudes) to the total CIR energy. A dominant first
  path (LOS) concentrates energy in its local window.
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{peak\_to\_noise}}: Ratio of the peak amplitude to
  STDEV\_NOISE. Higher SNR generally corresponds to a cleaner, more
  direct signal path.
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{amplitude\_ratio}}: Ratio of this path's amplitude to
  the other detected path's amplitude. Encodes the relative dominance of
  the two paths.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{CIR Statistical Features (5
features)}\label{cir-statistical-features-5-features}

These features describe the overall power delay profile (PDP) shape,
which differs systematically between LOS and NLOS:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{rms\_delay\_spread}}: Root mean squared delay spread,
  the standard deviation of the PDP around its mean excess delay. Higher
  values indicate more spread-out multipath energy (common in NLOS).
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{mean\_excess\_delay}}: The first moment of the PDP,
  representing the average delay of the received energy.
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{kurtosis\_full}}: Kurtosis of the entire 1016-sample
  CIR. LOS CIRs tend to be more ``peaky.''
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{max\_to\_mean}}: Ratio of the CIR maximum amplitude to
  its mean. Higher ratios indicate concentrated, dominant peaks.
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{tail\_energy\_ratio}}: Fraction of total CIR energy
  arriving after the detected path index, capturing the extent of
  multipath energy.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Shared Scalar Features (9 hardware features + 3
derived)}\label{shared-scalar-features-9-hardware-features-3-derived}

Nine hardware diagnostic features from the Decawave DWM1000 are included
unchanged (same for both paths of a sample): FP\_AMP1, FP\_AMP2,
FP\_AMP3, STDEV\_NOISE, CIR\_PWR, MAX\_NOISE, RXPACC, FRAME\_LEN,
PREAM\_LEN.

Three derived features are computed:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{path\_delay\_separation}}:
  \texttt{path2\_idx\ -\ path1\_idx}, the temporal gap between the two
  detected paths in nanoseconds. Larger separation indicates longer
  additional propagation distance for Path 2.
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{path1\_to\_fp\_offset}}:
  \texttt{path1\_idx\ -\ FP\_IDX}, how much the detected Path 1 deviates
  from the hardware's reported first-path index.
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{relative\_power}}: \texttt{FP\_AMP1\ /\ CIR\_PWR}, the
  fraction of total CIR power attributable to the first-path amplitude.
  A strong LOS signal concentrates power in the first path.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Classification Models}\label{classification-models}

\paragraph{Classifier Rationale}\label{classifier-rationale}

The selected classifier set covers the key comparison axes for this
project: linear versus non-linear boundaries, feature-engineered tabular
learning versus end-to-end sequence learning, and bagging versus
boosting tree ensembles. This set provides a practical comparison
baseline, so the emphasis is on rigorous interpretation and fair
cross-pipeline reporting rather than expanding the model list further.

\paragraph{Logistic Regression}\label{logistic-regression}

A linear baseline model with L2 regularization, trained with
\texttt{balanced} class weights to account for the 25/75 LOS/NLOS
imbalance. The linear decision boundary provides a lower bound on
achievable performance and helps assess whether the classification
problem is approximately linearly separable. Training uses
\texttt{max\_iter=1000} with the \texttt{lbfgs} solver.

\paragraph{SVM (RBF)}\label{svm-rbf}

An RBF-kernel SVM is included as a non-linear margin-based baseline.
Because SVM training scales poorly with sample count, the implementation
uses a fixed-size random subsample of the training set (up to 15,000
rows),
\texttt{class\_weight=\textquotesingle{}balanced\textquotesingle{}}, and
GridSearchCV over \texttt{C} and \texttt{gamma}. This model is useful as
a contrast point, but it is not expected to match the strongest tree
ensembles on this expanded dataset.

\paragraph{Random Forest}\label{random-forest}

An ensemble of decision trees using bagging (bootstrap aggregation)
{[}9{]}. Each tree is trained on a random subset of the training data
with a random subset of features considered at each split. The
aggregated vote of 300-500 trees provides variance reduction and
generally strong accuracy. Hyperparameters are tuned using GridSearchCV
over \texttt{n\_estimators} in \{300, 500\}, \texttt{max\_depth} in
\{20, None\}, and \texttt{min\_samples\_leaf} in \{1, 3\}, with 5-fold
stratified cross-validation optimizing weighted F1 score. Class
weighting is applied for imbalance handling.

\paragraph{Gradient Boosted Trees
(HistGradientBoosting)}\label{gradient-boosted-trees-histgradientboosting}

Scikit-learn's histogram-based gradient boosting classifier is used as
an efficient boosting implementation for larger tabular datasets. It
builds trees sequentially, with each tree fitting the residuals of the
previous ensemble. Sample weights are computed from class frequencies to
handle the LOS/NLOS imbalance (HistGBT does not natively support
\texttt{class\_weight}). GridSearchCV tunes \texttt{learning\_rate}
\(\in\) \{0.05, 0.1\}, \texttt{max\_iter} \(\in\) \{200, 500\}, and
\texttt{max\_depth} \(\in\) \{4, 6\}.

\paragraph{XGBoost}\label{xgboost}

An optimized gradient boosting implementation with built-in L1/L2
regularization, column subsampling, and row subsampling to prevent
overfitting {[}8{]}. The \texttt{scale\_pos\_weight} parameter is set to
the negative/positive class ratio to handle imbalance. GridSearchCV
tunes \texttt{n\_estimators} in \{200, 500\}, \texttt{max\_depth} in
\{4, 6, 8\}, \texttt{learning\_rate} in \{0.01, 0.05, 0.1\}, and
\texttt{subsample} in \{0.8, 1.0\}.

\subsubsection{CNN+Transformer
Architecture}\label{cnntransformer-architecture}

The \texttt{CIRTransformerClassifier} is a hybrid deep learning
architecture that processes the raw 1016-sample CIR waveform end-to-end.

\paragraph{Multi-Scale Convolutional First
Layer}\label{multi-scale-convolutional-first-layer}

The first layer applies three parallel 1D convolutions with kernel sizes
3, 7, and 15, each operating on the raw CIR input. Their outputs are
concatenated to 32 channels. This \textbf{multi-scale} design
simultaneously captures:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Fine-grained features (kernel=3): individual sample transitions, sharp
  peaks
\item
  Medium-scale features (kernel=7): rise/decay slopes, peak shapes
\item
  Broad features (kernel=15): multipath envelope patterns
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Residual CNN Blocks}\label{residual-cnn-blocks}

Two residual CNN blocks progressively down-sample the feature sequence:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Block 1: 32 to 64 channels, kernel=5, MaxPool(2): reduces sequence
  length from 508 to 254 (an initial MaxPool(2) reduces the 1016-sample
  input to 508 before the residual blocks)
\item
  Block 2: 64 to 128 channels, kernel=3, MaxPool(2): reduces to 127
\end{itemize}

Each residual block applies Conv→BN→ReLU→Conv→BN, adds the (projected)
input shortcut, applies ReLU, and pools. Residual connections {[}14{]}
improve gradient flow for deeper networks.

\paragraph{Transformer Encoder}\label{transformer-encoder}

The 127-step sequence of 128-dimensional embeddings is processed by a
2-layer Transformer encoder with 4 attention heads and feed-forward
dimension 256. Before the transformer, sinusoidal positional encodings
are added to give the model access to temporal position information.

The transformer's \textbf{self-attention mechanism} allows every
position in the compressed CIR sequence to attend to every other
position, capturing long-range dependencies between the first-path peak
and distant multipath components.

\paragraph{Classification Head}\label{classification-head}

Global average pooling collapses the 127-step sequence to a single
128-dimensional vector. This is concatenated with 11 scalar features
(scaled hardware diagnostics) to form a 139-dimensional vector, then
passed through a two-layer MLP (139→64→1) with ReLU and Dropout(0.1) to
produce a binary logit.

\paragraph{Training Details}\label{training-details}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Optimizer}: Adam {[}15{]} with initial learning rate 1e-3
\item
  \textbf{Loss}: Binary cross-entropy with logits (BCEWithLogitsLoss)
\item
  \textbf{Label smoothing}: Targets are soft-labeled using a binary
  adaptation of label smoothing {[}12{]} with ε = 0.05 (0.975 for
  positive, 0.025 for negative) to reduce overconfidence
\item
  \textbf{Learning rate schedule}: ReduceLROnPlateau (patience=2,
  factor=0.5)
\item
  \textbf{Early stopping}: Patience=5 epochs on validation loss
\item
  \textbf{Batch size}: 256
\item
  \textbf{Hardware}: Auto-detected backend (CUDA GPU, else Apple MPS,
  else CPU)
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Scope of Additional Models}\label{scope-of-additional-models}

Beyond the core tabular and deep models, the evaluation also reports
ensemble averaging, stacked generalization, and unsupervised clustering
diagnostics. These additions are treated as complementary analyses that
test robustness and feature-space structure, while the main classifier
narrative remains centered on the strongest supervised baselines and the
raw-CIR deep model.

\subsubsection{K-Means Clustering}\label{k-means-clustering}

K-Means with k=2 is applied to the expanded two-path 25-feature dataset
used by the supervised tabular pipeline. In the current implementation,
clustering is run directly on these engineered features without an
additional StandardScaler stage inside \texttt{run\_kmeans\_analysis}.
Since cluster labels are arbitrary (cluster 0 could map to either LOS or
NLOS), both possible assignments are tested and the one maximizing
accuracy is selected. Three metrics are reported:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Accuracy}: With optimal cluster-to-label mapping
\item
  \textbf{Silhouette score}: Measures cluster compactness and separation
  (range {[}-1, 1{]})
\item
  \textbf{Adjusted Rand Index (ARI)}: Label-permutation-invariant
  measure of cluster-label agreement
\end{itemize}

Under this evaluated expanded-set configuration, clustering remains
\textbf{weak}: K-Means achieves \textbf{0.5700 test accuracy} with
\textbf{ARI = -0.0099} (essentially random agreement --- slightly
\emph{worse} than chance alignment after optimal mapping), indicating
only very limited recovery of the
supervised LOS/NLOS structure. PCA is used to project the 25-dimensional
feature space to 2D for visualization
(\texttt{plots/14\_clustering.png}), but the resulting plot should be
read as evidence of substantial overlap rather than strong unsupervised
separation.

\paragraph{DBSCAN}\label{dbscan}

Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise (DBSCAN) is
applied as a complementary unsupervised method that, unlike K-Means,
does not require specifying the number of clusters in advance. DBSCAN
groups densely connected points into clusters and marks isolated points
as noise, enabling discovery of clusters with arbitrary shapes. This
makes it better suited to detecting non-convex class boundaries that
K-Means, with its spherical cluster assumption, cannot represent.

Features are standardized internally with \texttt{StandardScaler} before
clustering, since DBSCAN relies on Euclidean distance for neighborhood
queries. The algorithm is configured with \texttt{eps=2.0} (maximum
neighborhood radius) and \texttt{min\_samples=10} (minimum points to
form a dense core region). Accuracy is evaluated on non-noise samples
only, using the optimal cluster-to-label mapping (same approach as
K-Means). PCA is used to project the feature space to 2D for
visualization alongside the K-Means results.

In the evaluated configuration, DBSCAN fragments the scaled feature
space into \textbf{9 small density clusters} that do not align with the
LOS/NLOS labels, rejecting roughly \textbf{12.7\% of points as noise}
and reaching only \textbf{0.5263 accuracy} on the clustered points.
This is consistent with the weak unsupervised separation narrative:
density connectivity in this 25-dimensional engineered feature space
recovers local neighborhood structure but not the supervised LOS/NLOS
boundary.

\subsubsection{Ensemble Methods}\label{ensemble-methods}

\textbf{Simple Averaging}: The predicted probability outputs from RF,
GBT, and XGBoost are averaged element-wise. This reduces model-specific
variance without additional training.

\textbf{Stacked Generalization}: \texttt{cross\_val\_predict} generates
out-of-fold probability predictions from each base model on the training
set. These predictions form a ``meta-feature'' matrix, on which a
Logistic Regression meta-learner is trained. This allows the
meta-learner to discover optimal per-model weights and capture
complementary error patterns.

\subsubsection{Distance Estimation}\label{distance-estimation}

Four regression models are trained separately for each path: -
\textbf{Ridge Regression}: L2-regularized linear regression (alpha=1.0),
serving as a linear baseline - \textbf{Random Forest Regressor}: 200
decision trees, captures non-linear feature-range relationships -
\textbf{Gradient Boosted Regressor}: 200 sequential boosted trees,
typically best for tabular regression - \textbf{XGBoost Regressor}:
Gradient-boosted trees with regularization and subsampling controls

\textbf{Path 1 distance labels}: The original hardware-measured RANGE
value (time-of-flight distance in meters).

\textbf{Path 2 distance labels}: Computed as:

\[d_2 = \mathrm{RANGE} + (\mathrm{path2\_idx} - \mathrm{FP\_IDX}) \times 0.2998 \ \mathrm{m/ns}\]

This converts the additional CIR sample offset between Path 2 and the
hardware first-path index into meters using the speed of light (0.2998
m/ns), giving an estimated physical propagation distance for the
secondary path.

For Path 2 estimation, the original RANGE measurement is added as an
extra input feature, since Path 2's distance is closely correlated with
Path 1's measured distance plus the multipath delay.

\subsubsection{Evaluation Criteria}\label{evaluation-criteria}

The following evaluation metrics are used across the different analysis
components:

\textbf{Classification Evaluation:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Confusion Matrix}: Displays True Positives, True Negatives,
  False Positives, and False Negatives, enabling detailed inspection of
  per-class error patterns (e.g., missed NLOS detections vs.~false NLOS
  alarms).
\item
  \textbf{ROC Curve and AUC}: The Receiver Operating Characteristic
  curve plots True Positive Rate against False Positive Rate across all
  classification thresholds. The Area Under the Curve (AUC) provides a
  single threshold-independent summary of discriminative quality, making
  it the primary cross-model comparison metric.
\item
  \textbf{Precision-Recall Curve}: Complements ROC analysis by focusing
  on the trade-off between precision (fraction of predicted NLOS that
  are truly NLOS) and recall (fraction of actual NLOS correctly
  detected), which is particularly informative under class imbalance.
\item
  \textbf{Accuracy}: Overall fraction of correct predictions. Reported
  alongside AUC but interpreted cautiously due to the 25/75 class
  imbalance in the expanded dataset.
\item
  \textbf{Weighted F1 Score}: Used as the optimization target in
  GridSearchCV hyperparameter tuning, balancing precision and recall
  across both classes with class-frequency weighting.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Regression Evaluation:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error)}: Measures the average
  magnitude of prediction errors in meters, penalizing large errors more
  heavily than small ones.
\item
  \textbf{MAE (Mean Absolute Error)}: Average absolute prediction error
  in meters, providing a more interpretable central-tendency error
  measure.
\item
  \textbf{R² (Coefficient of Determination)}: Fraction of target
  variance explained by the model. \(R^2 = 1\) indicates perfect
  prediction; \(R^2 = 0\) indicates the model is no better than
  predicting the mean.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Clustering Evaluation:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Silhouette Score}: Measures how similar each point is to its
  own cluster compared to the nearest neighboring cluster, ranging from
  -1 (poor) to +1 (well-separated clusters).
\item
  \textbf{Adjusted Rand Index (ARI)}: A label-permutation-invariant
  measure of agreement between cluster assignments and true labels,
  corrected for chance. ARI = 0 indicates random-level agreement; ARI =
  1 indicates perfect agreement.
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\subsection{Pseudocode}\label{pseudocode}

\subsubsection{Algorithm 1: Two-Path Peak
Detection}\label{algorithm-1-two-path-peak-detection}

\begin{verbatim}
Input:  CIR waveform c[0..1015], first path index FP_IDX
Output: Path 1 peak (p1, a1), Path 2 peak (p2, a2)

1.  lo ← max(0, FP_IDX - 10)
2.  hi ← min(1015, FP_IDX + 10)
3.  p1 ← lo + argmax(c[lo..hi])
4.  a1 ← c[p1]

5.  kernel ← [1/3, 1/3, 1/3]
6.  c_smooth ← convolve(c, kernel, mode='same')

7.  threshold ← 0.02 * a1
8.  candidates ← find_peaks(c_smooth,
                             height=threshold,
                             distance=15,
                             prominence=threshold)

9.  Remove any candidate within |candidate - p1| <= 15

10. If no candidates remain:
11.     p2 ← 0; a2 ← 0.0; Return

12. p2 ← candidate with maximum prominence
13. a2 ← c[p2]   # read from unsmoothed CIR
14. Return p1, a1, p2, a2
\end{verbatim}

\subsubsection{Algorithm 2: CNN+Transformer
Training}\label{algorithm-2-cnntransformer-training}

\begin{verbatim}
Input:  Training set {(CIR_i, scalars_i, y_i)} for i = 1..N
Output: Trained model f_theta with best validation weights

1.  Initialize f_theta with random weights (He initialization)
2.  best_loss ← infinity; patience_count ← 0; best_weights ← null

3.  For epoch = 1 to 50:
4.      For each mini-batch B of size 256:
5.          y_B_smooth ← y_B * 0.95 + 0.025   # label smoothing (ε = 0.05)
6.          logits ← f_theta(CIR_B, scalars_B)
7.          L_train ← BCEWithLogitsLoss(logits, y_B_smooth)
8.          Backpropagate L_train; update theta via Adam

9.      Compute validation loss L_val on held-out validation set

10.     If L_val < best_loss:
11.         best_loss ← L_val
12.         best_weights ← copy(theta)
13.         patience_count ← 0
14.     Else:
15.         patience_count += 1
16.         Adjust learning_rate via ReduceLROnPlateau

17.     If patience_count >= 5:
18.         Break  # early stopping

19. Restore theta ← best_weights
20. Return f_theta
\end{verbatim}

\subsubsection{Algorithm 3: Main Pipeline
Orchestration}\label{algorithm-3-main-pipeline-orchestration}

\begin{verbatim}
Input:  7 CSV files from 7 indoor environments
Output: Classification results, regression results, visualizations

1.  Load 7 CSV files; concatenate to 42,000 x 1032 DataFrame

2.  Preprocessing:
    a. Drop constant columns CH, BITRATE, PRFR, ENV_ID
       (retain 11 scalar model features)
    b. Divide all CIR columns by RXPACC
       (per-preamble-pulse normalization)
    c. Replace NaN/Inf with 0
    d. Stratified 80/20 train/test split (33,596 / 8,400)
    e. Fit StandardScaler on training split;
       transform train/test scalar features

3.  Two-path peak detection (Algorithm 1) on 41,996 usable CIRs
    -> path1_idx, path1_amp, path2_idx, path2_amp

4.  Feature engineering (25 features per path)
    -> features_df (83,992 x 25), labels_cls (83,992), labels_range (83,992)

5.  ML classification (on 83,992-row two-path expanded dataset):
    a. Logistic Regression (no GridSearchCV, balanced weights)
    b. SVM (RBF, GridSearchCV on a 15k-sample subsample)
    c. Random Forest (GridSearchCV, 5-fold stratified CV)
    d. Gradient Boosted Trees (HistGBT, GridSearchCV)
    e. XGBoost (GridSearchCV)

6.  Deep learning (reported from original-split raw-CIR pipeline):
    Train CNN+Transformer (Algorithm 2) on raw CIR waveforms

7.  Synthetic data experiment:
    a. SMOTE (target_ratio=0.5, partial rebalancing) -> retrain RF -> compare
    b. CIR augmentation (3x) -> augmented DL training set -> retrain -> compare

8.  K-Means unsupervised baseline (k=2) on expanded two-path 25-feature vectors

9.  Ensemble methods:
    a. Simple average of RF + GBT + XGBoost probabilities
    b. Stacked generalization
       (LR meta-learner on cross-val predictions)

10. Distance estimation (4 regressors each):
    a. Path 1: 25-feature input, target = RANGE
    b. Path 2: 25-feature + RANGE input,
       target = RANGE + offset * 0.2998

11. Report classification, regression, clustering,
    and visualization outputs

12. Generate 14 visualizations
\end{verbatim}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\section{Source Code}\label{source-code}

The full source code is available at:
\url{https://github.com/hoshinoht/csc3105-project}

The analyses above establish the empirical findings; the excerpts below
summarize the implementation components that produce those outputs.

The listings below are trimmed excerpts chosen to show the core logic
while keeping the report readable in PDF form.

\subsection{main.py - Pipeline
Orchestration}\label{main.py---pipeline-orchestration}

The main pipeline coordinates all seven stages: loading, preprocessing,
peak detection, feature engineering, classification, regression, and
visualization.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ main():}
\NormalTok{    df\_raw }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ load\_dataset()}
\NormalTok{    df }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ preprocess(df\_raw)}
\NormalTok{    df\_scaled, train\_idx, test\_idx, scaler }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ scale\_and\_split(df)}

\NormalTok{    path1\_idx, path1\_amp, path2\_idx, path2\_amp }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ extract\_two\_paths(df)}
\NormalTok{    features\_df, labels\_cls, labels\_range, path\_ids }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ build\_features(}
\NormalTok{        df, path1\_idx, path1\_amp, path2\_idx, path2\_amp}
\NormalTok{    )}

\NormalTok{    cls\_results }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ train\_classifiers(X\_train\_cls, y\_train\_cls, X\_test\_cls, y\_test\_cls)}
\NormalTok{    ensemble\_results }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ build\_ensemble(}
\NormalTok{        cls\_results, X\_train\_cls, y\_train\_cls, X\_test\_cls, y\_test\_cls}
\NormalTok{    )}

\NormalTok{    reg\_results\_p1 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ train\_regressors(X\_train\_p1, y\_train\_p1, X\_test\_p1, y\_test\_p1, }\StringTok{"Path 1"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    reg\_results\_p2 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ train\_regressors(X\_train\_p2, y\_train\_p2, X\_test\_p2, y\_test\_p2, }\StringTok{"Path 2"}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{    viz.plot\_class\_distribution(df\_raw[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}NLOS\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{].values, labels\_cls)}
\NormalTok{    viz.plot\_roc\_curves(cls\_results)}
\NormalTok{    viz.plot\_confusion\_matrices(cls\_results, y\_test\_cls)}
\NormalTok{    viz.plot\_predicted\_vs\_actual(}
\NormalTok{        reg\_results\_p1, y\_test\_p1, reg\_results\_p2, y\_test\_p2}
\NormalTok{    )}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{src/peak\_detection.py - Two-Path
Extraction}\label{srcpeak_detection.py---two-path-extraction}

This module implements the two-path peak detection algorithm described
in Section 3.1.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ extract\_two\_paths(df):}
\NormalTok{    cir\_cols }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [c }\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ c }\KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ df.columns }\ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ c.startswith(}\StringTok{"CIR"}\NormalTok{) }\KeywordTok{and}\NormalTok{ c }\OperatorTok{!=} \StringTok{"CIR\_PWR"}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{    cir\_data }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ df[cir\_cols].values}
\NormalTok{    fp\_idx\_raw }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ df[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}FP\_IDX\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{].values}

    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(n\_samples):}
\NormalTok{        cir }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ cir\_data[i]}
\NormalTok{        fp }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{int}\NormalTok{(fp\_idx\_raw[i])}

\NormalTok{        lo }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{max}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, fp }\OperatorTok{{-}} \DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{        hi }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{min}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1016}\NormalTok{, fp }\OperatorTok{+} \DecValTok{11}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{        path1\_idx[i] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ lo }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ np.argmax(cir[lo:hi])}
\NormalTok{        path1\_amp[i] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ cir[path1\_idx[i]]}

\NormalTok{        peaks, props }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ find\_peaks(}
\NormalTok{            np.convolve(cir, np.ones(}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{/} \FloatTok{3.0}\NormalTok{, mode}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{"same"}\NormalTok{),}
\NormalTok{            height}\OperatorTok{=}\FloatTok{0.02} \OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ path1\_amp[i],}
\NormalTok{            distance}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{15}\NormalTok{,}
\NormalTok{            prominence}\OperatorTok{=}\FloatTok{0.02} \OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ path1\_amp[i],}
\NormalTok{        )}

\NormalTok{        valid }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ np.}\BuiltInTok{abs}\NormalTok{(peaks }\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ path1\_idx[i]) }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{15}
        \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ np.}\BuiltInTok{any}\NormalTok{(valid):}
\NormalTok{            best }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ np.argmax(props[}\StringTok{"prominences"}\NormalTok{][valid])}
\NormalTok{            path2\_idx[i] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ peaks[valid][best]}
\NormalTok{            path2\_amp[i] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ cir[path2\_idx[i]]}

    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ path1\_idx, path1\_amp, path2\_idx, path2\_amp}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{src/feature\_engineering.py - Per-Path Feature
Computation}\label{srcfeature_engineering.py---per-path-feature-computation}

This module builds the 25-feature vectors for each detected path and
assembles the expanded two-path dataset.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ build\_features(df, path1\_idx, path1\_amp, path2\_idx, path2\_amp):}
\NormalTok{    p1\_feats }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ \_compute\_path\_features(}
\NormalTok{        cir\_data, path1\_idx, path1\_amp, path2\_amp, stdev\_noise}
\NormalTok{    )}
\NormalTok{    p2\_feats }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ \_compute\_path\_features(}
\NormalTok{        cir\_data, path2\_idx, path2\_amp, path1\_amp, stdev\_noise}
\NormalTok{    )}

\NormalTok{    labels\_p1 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ original\_nlos.copy()}
\NormalTok{    labels\_p2 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ np.ones(}\BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(df), dtype}\OperatorTok{=}\BuiltInTok{int}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    range\_p2 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ original\_range }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ (path2\_idx }\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ fp\_idx) }\OperatorTok{*} \FloatTok{0.2998}  \CommentTok{\# m/ns}

\NormalTok{    features\_df }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.concat([path1\_df, path2\_df], ignore\_index}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    labels\_cls }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ np.concatenate([labels\_p1, labels\_p2])}
\NormalTok{    labels\_range }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ np.concatenate([range\_p1, range\_p2])}

    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ features\_df, labels\_cls, labels\_range, path\_ids}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{src/dl\_models.py - CIRTransformerClassifier
Architecture}\label{srcdl_models.py---cirtransformerclassifier-architecture}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{class}\NormalTok{ CIRTransformerClassifier(nn.Module):}
    \KeywordTok{def} \FunctionTok{\_\_init\_\_}\NormalTok{(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{, n\_scalar}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{11}\NormalTok{, cnn\_channels}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{128}\NormalTok{, n\_heads}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{):}
        \BuiltInTok{super}\NormalTok{().}\FunctionTok{\_\_init\_\_}\NormalTok{()}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.multi\_scale }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ MultiScaleConv(out\_channels}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{32}\NormalTok{)}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.pool1 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ nn.MaxPool1d(}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.res\_block2 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ ResidualCNNBlock(}\DecValTok{32}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{64}\NormalTok{, kernel\_size}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{)}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.res\_block3 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ ResidualCNNBlock(}\DecValTok{64}\NormalTok{, cnn\_channels, kernel\_size}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.pos\_enc }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ PositionalEncoding(cnn\_channels, max\_len}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{512}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{        encoder\_layer }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ nn.TransformerEncoderLayer(}
\NormalTok{            d\_model}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{cnn\_channels, nhead}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{n\_heads,}
\NormalTok{            dim\_feedforward}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{cnn\_channels }\OperatorTok{*} \DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{,}
\NormalTok{            dropout}\OperatorTok{=}\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{,}
\NormalTok{            batch\_first}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{,}
\NormalTok{        )}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.transformer }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ nn.TransformerEncoder(encoder\_layer, num\_layers}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.head }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ nn.Sequential(}
\NormalTok{            nn.Linear(cnn\_channels }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ n\_scalar, }\DecValTok{64}\NormalTok{),}
\NormalTok{            nn.ReLU(),}
\NormalTok{            nn.Dropout(}\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{),}
\NormalTok{            nn.Linear(}\DecValTok{64}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{),}
\NormalTok{        )}

    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ forward(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{, cir, scalars):}
\NormalTok{        x }\OperatorTok{=} \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.multi\_scale(cir.unsqueeze(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{        x }\OperatorTok{=} \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.res\_block2(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.pool1(x))}
\NormalTok{        x }\OperatorTok{=} \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.res\_block3(x).permute(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{        x }\OperatorTok{=} \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.transformer(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.pos\_enc(x)).mean(dim}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.head(torch.cat([x, scalars], dim}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{src/classification.py - GridSearchCV
Training}\label{srcclassification.py---gridsearchcv-training}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ train\_classifiers(X\_train, y\_train, X\_test, y\_test):}
\NormalTok{    cv }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ StratifiedKFold(n\_splits}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{, shuffle}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    lr }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ LogisticRegression(class\_weight}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}balanced\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, max\_iter}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{1000}\NormalTok{, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    lr.fit(X\_train, y\_train)}

\NormalTok{    svm }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ SVC(kernel}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}rbf\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, probability}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{, class\_weight}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}balanced\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    param\_grid\_svm }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ \{}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}C\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{], }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}gamma\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}scale\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}auto\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{]\}}
\NormalTok{    svm\_idx }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ np.random.RandomState(}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{).choice(}\BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(X\_train), }\BuiltInTok{min}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{15000}\NormalTok{, }\BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(X\_train)), replace}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{False}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    gs\_svm }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ GridSearchCV(svm, param\_grid\_svm, scoring}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}f1\_weighted\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, cv}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{cv, n\_jobs}\OperatorTok{={-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    gs\_svm.fit(X\_train[svm\_idx], y\_train[svm\_idx])}

\NormalTok{    gs\_rf }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ GridSearchCV(RandomForestClassifier(class\_weight}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}balanced\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{, n\_jobs}\OperatorTok{={-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{), \{}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}n\_estimators\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{300}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{500}\NormalTok{],}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}max\_depth\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{, }\VariableTok{None}\NormalTok{],}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}min\_samples\_leaf\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{],}
\NormalTok{    \}, scoring}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}f1\_weighted\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, cv}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{cv, n\_jobs}\OperatorTok{={-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    gs\_rf.fit(X\_train, y\_train)}

\NormalTok{    gbt }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ HistGradientBoostingClassifier(random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    class\_ratio }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ (y\_train }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{).}\BuiltInTok{sum}\NormalTok{() }\OperatorTok{/} \BuiltInTok{max}\NormalTok{((y\_train }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{).}\BuiltInTok{sum}\NormalTok{(), }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    sample\_weight }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ np.where(y\_train }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{1.0} \OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{ class\_ratio, }\FloatTok{1.0}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    sample\_weight }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ sample\_weight }\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{ sample\_weight.mean()}
\NormalTok{    gs\_gbt }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ GridSearchCV(gbt, \{}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}learning\_rate\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\FloatTok{0.05}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{],}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}max\_iter\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{200}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{500}\NormalTok{],}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}max\_depth\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{],}
\NormalTok{    \}, scoring}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}f1\_weighted\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, cv}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{cv, n\_jobs}\OperatorTok{={-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    gs\_gbt.fit(X\_train, y\_train, sample\_weight}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{sample\_weight)}

\NormalTok{    n\_neg }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{int}\NormalTok{((y\_train }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{).}\BuiltInTok{sum}\NormalTok{())}
\NormalTok{    n\_pos }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{int}\NormalTok{((y\_train }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{).}\BuiltInTok{sum}\NormalTok{())}
\NormalTok{    xgb }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ XGBClassifier(eval\_metric}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}logloss\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, scale\_pos\_weight}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{n\_neg }\OperatorTok{/} \BuiltInTok{max}\NormalTok{(n\_pos, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{), random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    gs\_xgb }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ GridSearchCV(xgb, \{}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}n\_estimators\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{200}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{500}\NormalTok{],}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}max\_depth\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{8}\NormalTok{],}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}learning\_rate\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\FloatTok{0.01}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{0.05}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{],}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}subsample\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\FloatTok{0.8}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{1.0}\NormalTok{],}
\NormalTok{    \}, scoring}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}f1\_weighted\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, cv}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{cv, n\_jobs}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    gs\_xgb.fit(X\_train, y\_train)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{src/regression.py - Distance Estimation
Models}\label{srcregression.py---distance-estimation-models}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ train\_regressors(X\_train, y\_train, X\_test, y\_test, path\_name}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{""}\NormalTok{):}
\NormalTok{    models }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ \{}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}Ridge Regression\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: Ridge(alpha}\OperatorTok{=}\FloatTok{1.0}\NormalTok{),}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}Random Forest Regressor\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: RandomForestRegressor(n\_estimators}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{200}\NormalTok{, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{),}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}Gradient Boosted Regressor\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: GradientBoostingRegressor(n\_estimators}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{200}\NormalTok{, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{),}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}XGBoost Regressor\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: XGBRegressor(}
\NormalTok{            n\_estimators}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{300}\NormalTok{,}
\NormalTok{            max\_depth}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{,}
\NormalTok{            learning\_rate}\OperatorTok{=}\FloatTok{0.05}\NormalTok{,}
\NormalTok{            subsample}\OperatorTok{=}\FloatTok{0.9}\NormalTok{,}
\NormalTok{            objective}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}reg:squarederror\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}
\NormalTok{            random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{,}
\NormalTok{        ),}
\NormalTok{    \}}

    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ name, model }\KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ models.items():}
\NormalTok{        model.fit(X\_train, y\_train)}
\NormalTok{        y\_pred }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ model.predict(X\_test)}
\NormalTok{        results[name] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ \{}
            \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}rmse\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: np.sqrt(mean\_squared\_error(y\_test, y\_pred)),}
            \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}mae\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: mean\_absolute\_error(y\_test, y\_pred),}
            \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}r2\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: r2\_score(y\_test, y\_pred),}
\NormalTok{        \}}

    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ results}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{src/synthetic\_data.py - SMOTE and CIR
Augmentation}\label{srcsynthetic_data.py---smote-and-cir-augmentation}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ apply\_smote(X\_train, y\_train, target\_ratio}\OperatorTok{=}\FloatTok{1.0}\NormalTok{, k\_neighbors}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{):  }\CommentTok{\# called with target\_ratio=0.5}
\NormalTok{    target\_count }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{int}\NormalTok{(majority\_count }\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ target\_ratio)}
\NormalTok{    n\_synthetic }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{max}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, target\_count }\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ minority\_count)}

\NormalTok{    nn }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ NearestNeighbors(n\_neighbors}\OperatorTok{=}\BuiltInTok{min}\NormalTok{(k\_neighbors }\OperatorTok{+} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(X\_minority)))}
\NormalTok{    nn.fit(X\_minority)}
\NormalTok{    \_, indices }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ nn.kneighbors(X\_minority)}

    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(n\_synthetic):}
\NormalTok{        idx }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ rng.randint(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(X\_minority))}
\NormalTok{        neighbor }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ indices[idx, rng.randint(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, indices.shape[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{])]}
\NormalTok{        lam }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ rng.uniform(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{        synthetic\_samples[i] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ X\_minority[idx] }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ lam }\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ (X\_minority[neighbor] }\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ X\_minority[idx])}

    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ np.vstack([X\_train, synthetic\_samples]), np.concatenate([y\_train, synthetic\_labels])}


\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ generate\_augmented\_cir(cir\_data, scalars, labels, augmentation\_factor}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, ...):}
    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ \_ }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(augmentation\_factor):}
\NormalTok{        aug\_cir }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ augment\_cir\_noise(cir\_data, noise\_level}\OperatorTok{=}\FloatTok{0.08}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{        aug\_cir }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ augment\_cir\_jitter(aug\_cir, max\_shift}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{        aug\_cir }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ augment\_cir\_amplitude(aug\_cir, (}\FloatTok{0.80}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{1.20}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{        all\_aug\_cir.append(aug\_cir)}

    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ np.vstack([cir\_data] }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ all\_aug\_cir), ...}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{src/clustering.py - K-Means Unsupervised
Analysis}\label{srcclustering.py---k-means-unsupervised-analysis}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ run\_kmeans\_analysis(X\_train, y\_train, X\_test, y\_test, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{):}
\NormalTok{    kmeans }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ KMeans(n\_clusters}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{random\_state, n\_init}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    train\_clusters }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ kmeans.fit\_predict(X\_train)}
\NormalTok{    test\_clusters }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ kmeans.predict(X\_test)}

\NormalTok{    acc\_a }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ accuracy\_score(y\_test, test\_clusters)}
\NormalTok{    acc\_b }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ accuracy\_score(y\_test, }\DecValTok{1} \OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ test\_clusters)}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ acc\_b }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}}\NormalTok{ acc\_a:}
\NormalTok{        test\_clusters }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{1} \OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ test\_clusters}
\NormalTok{        train\_clusters }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{1} \OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ train\_clusters}
\NormalTok{        best\_acc }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ acc\_b}
    \ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{:}
\NormalTok{        best\_acc }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ acc\_a}

\NormalTok{    sil\_score }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ silhouette\_score(X\_test, kmeans.predict(X\_test))}
\NormalTok{    ari }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ adjusted\_rand\_score(y\_test, test\_clusters)}
\NormalTok{    pca }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ PCA(n\_components}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{random\_state)}
\NormalTok{    X\_test\_2d }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pca.fit(X\_train).transform(X\_test)}

    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ \{}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}test\_accuracy\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: best\_acc,}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}silhouette\_test\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: sil\_score,}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}ari\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: ari,}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}X\_test\_2d\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: X\_test\_2d,}
\NormalTok{    \}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\subsection{src/preprocessing.py - Data Cleaning
Pipeline}\label{srcpreprocessing.py---data-cleaning-pipeline}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{CONSTANT\_COLS }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}CH\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}BITRATE\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}PRFR\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}ENV\_ID\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{SCALAR\_FEATURES }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}RANGE\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}FP\_IDX\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}FP\_AMP1\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}FP\_AMP2\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}FP\_AMP3\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}
                   \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}STDEV\_NOISE\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}CIR\_PWR\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}MAX\_NOISE\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}RXPACC\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}
                   \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}FRAME\_LEN\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}PREAM\_LEN\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{]}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ preprocess(df):}
\NormalTok{    df.drop(columns}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{CONSTANT\_COLS, inplace}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    cir\_cols }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [c }\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ c }\KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ df.columns }\ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ c.startswith(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}CIR\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{) }\KeywordTok{and}\NormalTok{ c }\OperatorTok{!=} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}CIR\_PWR\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{    rxpacc }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ df[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}RXPACC\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{].values[:, np.newaxis]}
\NormalTok{    df[cir\_cols] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ df[cir\_cols].values }\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{ rxpacc}
\NormalTok{    df[cir\_cols] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ df[cir\_cols].replace([np.inf, }\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{np.inf], np.nan).fillna(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{)}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ df}


\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ scale\_and\_split(df, test\_size}\OperatorTok{=}\FloatTok{0.2}\NormalTok{, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{42}\NormalTok{):}
\NormalTok{    y }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ df[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}NLOS\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{].values}
\NormalTok{    train\_idx, test\_idx }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ train\_test\_split(}
\NormalTok{        np.arange(}\BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(df)), test\_size}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{test\_size,}
\NormalTok{        stratify}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{y, random\_state}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{random\_state,}
\NormalTok{    )}

\NormalTok{    scaler }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ StandardScaler()}
\NormalTok{    df\_scaled }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ df.copy()}
\NormalTok{    scaler.fit(df.iloc[train\_idx][SCALAR\_FEATURES])}
\NormalTok{    df\_scaled[SCALAR\_FEATURES] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ scaler.transform(df[SCALAR\_FEATURES])}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ df\_scaled, train\_idx, test\_idx, scaler}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\section{Results and Analysis}\label{results-and-analysis}

\subsection{Data Preparation}\label{data-preparation}

\subsubsection{Dataset Overview}\label{dataset-overview}

The raw dataset consists of 42,000 UWB CIR measurements collected across
7 indoor environments. The dataset is already balanced with exactly
21,000 LOS and 21,000 NLOS samples, making initial class imbalance
handling unnecessary at the raw level. After preprocessing and removal
of 4 degenerate samples, \textbf{41,996 usable measurements} remain.
Each measurement contains:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  14 scalar hardware features (+ ENV\_ID metadata column in raw files;
  11 scalar model features retained after dropping constants)
\item
  1016 CIR amplitude samples at 1 ns time resolution
\item
  1 binary target label (NLOS: 0 or 1)
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Data Reduction: Constant Column
Removal}\label{data-reduction-constant-column-removal}

Four metadata/protocol columns (\texttt{CH} (UWB channel number),
\texttt{BITRATE} (data rate), \texttt{PRFR} (pulse repetition
frequency), and \texttt{ENV\_ID}) are \textbf{constant or
non-informative for model fitting in this pipeline}. These are removed
before modeling, leaving 11 scalar model features. Retaining these
columns would add noise to distance-based algorithms and inflate
feature-importance computations.

\subsubsection{Data Transformation: CIR
Normalization}\label{data-transformation-cir-normalization}

The raw CIR amplitudes are accumulated over \texttt{RXPACC} preamble
symbols; the Decawave hardware integrates the CIR over multiple preamble
periods to improve SNR. As a result, raw amplitudes are proportional to
RXPACC and are not directly comparable across samples with different
RXPACC values. \textbf{Per-preamble-pulse normalization} divides each of
the 1016 CIR samples by the corresponding RXPACC value:

\[\mathrm{CIR\_normalized}[i] = \frac{\mathrm{CIR\_raw}[i]}{\mathrm{RXPACC}}\]

After normalization, any resulting NaN or Inf values (from RXPACC = 0
edge cases) are replaced with 0.

\subsubsection{Feature Scaling}\label{feature-scaling}

The 11 remaining scalar features have very different magnitudes and
units: RANGE is in meters (typically 0.1--15 m), FP\_IDX is a sample
index (0--1015), CIR\_PWR is a power value, RXPACC is a count (roughly
1000), etc. Algorithms sensitive to feature scale, especially Logistic
Regression and neural networks, would be dominated by large-magnitude
features without scaling.

\textbf{StandardScaler} transforms each scalar feature to zero mean and
unit variance:

\[z = \frac{x - \mu}{\sigma}\]

The scaler is fit \textbf{only on training data} and applied to both
train and test sets, preventing data leakage.

\subsubsection{Train/Test Splitting}\label{traintest-splitting}

A \textbf{stratified 80/20 split} is applied to ensure both train and
test sets maintain the original class balance of the usable dataset.
This produces approximately: - Training set: 33,596 samples - Test set:
8,400 samples

Train and test indices are preserved and applied consistently to both
the usable original-sample dataset and the expanded two-path dataset.

\subsubsection{Two-Path Dataset
Expansion}\label{two-path-dataset-expansion}

After peak detection and feature engineering, each usable sample becomes
\textbf{two rows} in the expanded dataset: one for Path 1, one for Path
2. This produces an \textbf{83,992-row} dataset with class counts
\textbf{20,999 LOS} and \textbf{62,993 NLOS}, i.e.~approximately a 25/75
LOS/NLOS imbalance.

\subsubsection{Engineered Feature Scaling for Scale-Sensitive
Models}\label{engineered-feature-scaling-for-scale-sensitive-models}

The two-path expansion produces a 25-feature matrix where features span
vastly different magnitude ranges. For example, \texttt{CIR\_PWR} takes
values in the hundreds of thousands while \texttt{energy\_ratio} is
bounded in {[}0, 1{]} and \texttt{rise\_time} typically falls between 1
and 10 samples. This disparity has no impact on tree-based models
(Random Forest, HistGradientBoosting, XGBoost), which partition data
using threshold comparisons on individual features independently and are
therefore scale-invariant by design.

However, three algorithm families in the pipeline are directly affected:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{SVM (RBF Kernel)}: Similarity between samples is computed via
  the RBF kernel \(K(x, x') = \exp(-\gamma \|x - x'\|^2)\), where
  \(\|x - x'\|^2 = \sum_{j=1}^{25}(x_j - x'_j)^2\). A single feature
  such as \texttt{CIR\_PWR} differing by 10,000 units contributes
  \(\mathcal{O}(10^8)\) to this sum, rendering all remaining features
  negligible. Without scaling, the SVM kernel becomes a function of
  \texttt{CIR\_PWR} alone.
\item
  \textbf{Logistic Regression}: Gradient descent weight updates are
  proportional to feature magnitude. Large-scale features dominate
  gradient steps, causing weights for physically meaningful small-scale
  features (e.g., \texttt{energy\_ratio}, \texttt{rise\_time}) to
  converge slowly or not at all.
\item
  \textbf{K-Means and DBSCAN}: Both assign cluster membership using
  Euclidean distance. Unscaled high-magnitude features dictate cluster
  geometry, producing groupings that reflect \texttt{CIR\_PWR} ranges
  rather than the LOS/NLOS signal structure.
\end{itemize}

Rather than globally scaling the engineered feature matrix (which would
be unnecessary for tree models and would obscure physical units in
feature importance plots), scaling is applied internally per model using
\texttt{sklearn.pipeline.Pipeline}. For clustering functions, a
\texttt{StandardScaler} is fit on the training partition internally
before any distance computation. This ensures scale-sensitive models
receive properly normalised inputs while tree-based model inputs remain
in their original physical units. The tabular ML pipeline is implemented
using scikit-learn {[}18{]}, and the deep learning pipeline uses PyTorch
{[}19{]}.

\subsubsection{Synthetic Data
Augmentation}\label{synthetic-data-augmentation}

Two augmentation strategies are explored and compared against the
non-augmented baseline:

\textbf{SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-Sampling Technique)} {[}13{]} is
applied to the ML training feature vectors. For each minority-class
(LOS) sample, SMOTE selects one of its k=5 nearest neighbors in
25-dimensional feature space and generates a new synthetic sample by
interpolating between them:

\[x_{\mathrm{synth}} = x_{\mathrm{orig}} + \lambda \cdot (x_{\mathrm{neighbor}} - x_{\mathrm{orig}}), \quad \lambda \sim \mathrm{Uniform}(0, 1)\]

Sufficient synthetic LOS samples are generated to reach a
minority/majority ratio of 0.5 (partial rebalancing), rather than full
50/50 balance.

\textbf{CIR Waveform Augmentation} is applied to generate 3× the
original training set for the deep learning model, using three
physically motivated perturbations applied in sequence:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Gaussian noise injection}:
  \(\mathrm{CIR}_{\mathrm{aug}} = \mathrm{CIR} + \epsilon\), where
  \(\epsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 0.08 \cdot \sigma_{\mathrm{CIR}})\);
  this simulates receiver thermal noise
\item
  \textbf{Temporal jitter}: Random shift of ±4 samples; this simulates
  clock synchronization imprecision
\item
  \textbf{Amplitude scaling}: Uniform random scale factor in {[}0.80,
  1.20{]}; this simulates path loss variation across distances
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Feature Importance}\label{feature-importance}

After training Random Forest on the 25-feature dataset, Gini
impurity-based feature importance reveals that features related to
\textbf{signal power, amplitude, and noise} are most discriminative. A
complementary RFECV analysis over the same Random Forest returns the
\textbf{full 25-feature set as optimal} under 3-fold cross-validated
accuracy --- that is, strict feature reduction is not supported.
However, the RFECV curve is nearly flat from roughly ten features
onward, meaning a smaller subset would sacrifice very little accuracy
in practice; this still reinforces the importance of path amplitude and
local SNR features at the top of the Gini ranking.

\subsubsection{Outlier Analysis}\label{outlier-analysis}

To examine whether extreme scalar values represent measurement errors or
meaningful propagation behavior, we performed \textbf{Tukey IQR outlier
analysis} on all 11 retained scalar features. Across the dataset,
\textbf{16.9\% of samples are outliers in at least one scalar feature}.

The outliers are not uniformly distributed across classes, and several
are physically informative rather than erroneous:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{FP\_IDX} outliers (4.18\%)}: \textbf{98.7\% NLOS},
  consistent with delayed first-path arrival under obstruction
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{RANGE} outliers (0.29\%)}: \textbf{100\% NLOS},
  reflecting extreme positive ranging bias
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{STDEV\_NOISE} outliers (4.56\%)}: \textbf{57.7\%
  NLOS}, indicating mixed behavior rather than a class-exclusive pattern
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{MAX\_NOISE} outliers (7.06\%)}: only \textbf{28.9\%
  NLOS}, so these extremes are not class-specific
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{CIR\_PWR} outliers (2.23\%)}: \textbf{42.2\% NLOS},
  again indicating mixed rather than purely NLOS-driven extremes
\end{itemize}

Only \textbf{4 degenerate samples} (with \texttt{RANGE\ =\ 0} or
\texttt{CIR\_PWR\ =\ 0}) were removed as likely hardware errors. The
remaining IQR outliers were intentionally retained for four reasons.
First, many outliers encode genuine NLOS signal characteristics that are
precisely what the classifier must learn. Second, removing
\textbf{16.9\%} of the dataset wholesale would be unnecessarily
destructive. Third, the main tabular classifiers used here (Random
Forest, Gradient Boosted Trees, and XGBoost) are inherently robust to
outliers. Fourth, the CNN+Transformer consumes StandardScaled scalar
inputs, which mitigates raw scale effects. For clustering, we report the
implementation's direct run on the expanded engineered features without
an additional scaling step.

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\subsection{Data Mining Results}\label{data-mining-results}

\subsubsection{Supervised
Classification}\label{supervised-classification}

\paragraph{Logistic Regression}\label{logistic-regression-1}

Logistic Regression provides the linear baseline. It models the log-odds
of NLOS classification as a linear combination of the 25 input features.
On the expanded two-path test set:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Accuracy}: 0.9185
\item
  \textbf{AUC}: 0.9730
\end{itemize}

The lower AUC compared to tree-based methods suggests that the LOS/NLOS
decision boundary in 25-dimensional feature space is
\textbf{non-linear}, and a linear classifier cannot capture all the
discriminative structure in the data.

\paragraph{Random Forest}\label{random-forest-1}

After GridSearchCV, the best Random Forest configuration achieves on the
expanded two-path test set:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Accuracy}: 0.9396
\item
  \textbf{AUC}: 0.9821
\end{itemize}

The accuracy improvement over Logistic Regression suggests the
importance of non-linear decision boundaries. The ensemble of trees
naturally handles feature interactions (e.g., the joint combination of
\texttt{energy\_ratio} and \texttt{peak\_to\_noise}) that linear models
cannot capture. Feature importances extracted from the trained forest
provide interpretable insight into which features matter most.

\paragraph{Gradient Boosted Trees}\label{gradient-boosted-trees}

The HistGradientBoostingClassifier delivers similarly strong
performance:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Accuracy}: 0.9312
\item
  \textbf{AUC}: 0.9821
\end{itemize}

Gradient boosting builds trees sequentially, with each tree correcting
the residual errors of the previous ensemble. The histogram-based
implementation is computationally efficient for larger tabular datasets
and, in this study, achieves competitive performance among the
tree-based baselines.

\paragraph{XGBoost}\label{xgboost-1}

XGBoost achieves the strongest single-model inline classification result
after GridSearchCV tuning:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Accuracy}: 0.9398
\item
  \textbf{AUC}: 0.9832
\end{itemize}

XGBoost's built-in regularization (L1 and L2 penalties on tree weights)
provides additional robustness against overfitting.

\paragraph{CNN+Transformer Deep
Learning}\label{cnntransformer-deep-learning}

The hybrid CNN+Transformer model is trained on the original-sample
raw-CIR pipeline rather than the expanded two-path set, since the raw
CIR is identical for both paths of a given sample. Because results are
pre-computed from this separate pipeline, they should be compared
qualitatively with the tabular benchmarks:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Accuracy}: 0.9368
\item
  \textbf{AUC}: 0.9827
\end{itemize}

With raw-CIR augmentation in that separate pipeline, the CNN+Transformer
reaches \textbf{0.9387 accuracy} and \textbf{0.9862 AUC}. Augmentation
trades a small amount of raw accuracy for a clear AUC improvement;
because this result comes from a different training workflow, it should
not be interpreted as direct superiority over the tabular ML models.

\paragraph{Ensemble Methods}\label{ensemble-methods-1}

\textbf{Ensemble (Average)}: Averaging RF, GBT, and XGBoost probability
predictions reduces model-specific variance. On the expanded two-path
test set, the ensemble reaches \textbf{0.9399 accuracy} and
\textbf{0.9832 AUC}.

\textbf{Ensemble (Stacked)}: The logistic regression meta-learner
trained on cross-validated base-model predictions slightly improves
accuracy to \textbf{0.9413} with \textbf{0.9829 AUC}, indicating that
most of the gain comes from combining strong tree-based learners rather
than from a dramatic change in ranking quality.

\subsubsection{Unsupervised K-Means
Clustering}\label{unsupervised-k-means-clustering}

K-Means (k=2) is applied to the expanded two-path 25-feature dataset
used by the tabular classifiers. In the evaluated implementation, this
clustering step does not apply an additional StandardScaler internally;
results therefore reflect the raw engineered feature magnitudes and the
inherent 25/75 class imbalance of the expanded labeling setup.

With optimal cluster-to-label mapping, K-Means reaches only
\textbf{0.5700 test accuracy} and \textbf{-0.0099 ARI} (essentially
random agreement). These values
indicate weak unsupervised label recovery rather than meaningful
unsupervised recovery of the LOS/NLOS boundary. PCA visualization of the
25-dimensional feature space projected to 2D in
\texttt{plots/14\_clustering.png} should therefore be interpreted
cautiously: overlap between classes remains substantial.

\subsubsection{Distance Estimation
(Regression)}\label{distance-estimation-regression}

\paragraph{Path 1 Distance Estimation}\label{path-1-distance-estimation}

Path 1 regression uses the 25 per-path features with the original RANGE
as target:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Ridge Regression}: RMSE = 1.6164 m, R² = 0.5407
\item
  \textbf{Random Forest Regressor}: RMSE = 1.3706 m, R² = 0.6698
\item
  \textbf{Gradient Boosted Regressor}: RMSE = 1.3877 m, R² = 0.6615
\item
  \textbf{XGBoost Regressor}: RMSE = 1.3715 m, R² = 0.6693
\end{itemize}

Path 1 regression is challenging because the target RANGE value includes
NLOS bias for NLOS samples {[}3{]}, {[}4{]}: the measured range is
systematically larger than the true distance, and the magnitude of the
bias varies by environment.

\paragraph{Path 2 Distance Estimation}\label{path-2-distance-estimation}

Path 2 regression uses the 25 per-path features plus the original RANGE
measurement as an additional feature:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Ridge Regression}: RMSE = 0.0000 m, R² = 1.0000 \emph{(see
  note below)}
\item
  \textbf{Random Forest Regressor}: RMSE = 0.4658 m, R² = 0.9997
\item
  \textbf{Gradient Boosted Regressor}: RMSE = 0.2900 m, R² = 0.9999
\item
  \textbf{XGBoost Regressor}: RMSE = 1.2238 m, R² = 0.9980
\end{itemize}

Path 2 achieves dramatically better regression performance because its
target is \textbf{analytically constrained} by how it is constructed
from RANGE and path timing. The perfect Ridge result should therefore
not be interpreted as evidence that Path 2 is an intrinsically easy
real-world regression task; rather, it reflects that the target is an
exact linear combination of features supplied as inputs.

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\subsection{Data Visualization}\label{data-visualization}

All core plots (01-14) are generated by \texttt{src/visualization.py}
and saved to the \texttt{plots/} directory. Each core plot is described
below with its physical and statistical interpretation. Additional
supplementary diagnostics (15-24) are included afterward using the same
\texttt{plots/} source directory.

\subsubsection{Plot 01: Class
Distribution}\label{plot-01-class-distribution}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={Class Distribution Before and After Two-Path Expansion}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/01_class_distribution.png}}
\caption{Class Distribution Before and After Two-Path Expansion}
\end{figure}

This bar chart shows two class distributions side by side. The left
group represents the \textbf{original 42,000 raw samples}: 21,000 LOS
(50\%) and 21,000 NLOS (50\%), a perfectly balanced dataset before final
preprocessing cleanup. The right group represents the \textbf{expanded
83,992 two-path dataset} built from the 41,996 usable samples: 20,999
LOS rows (25.0\%) and 62,993 NLOS rows (75.0\%).

This visualization immediately explains why class weighting is necessary
and why SMOTE is reasonable to test as an augmentation option: the
two-path expansion naturally creates a 3:1 NLOS:LOS imbalance.

\subsubsection{Plot 02: Feature Distributions by
Class}\label{plot-02-feature-distributions-by-class}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={Feature Distributions (LOS vs NLOS) for Key Scalar Features}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/02_feature_distributions.png}}
\caption{Feature Distributions (LOS vs NLOS) for Key Scalar Features}
\end{figure}

Kernel density estimate (KDE) plots overlay the per-class distributions
of key scalar features. Features such as \texttt{CIR\_PWR},
\texttt{FP\_AMP1}, and \texttt{STDEV\_NOISE} show substantial separation
between LOS (blue) and NLOS (orange) distributions. For example:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{CIR\_PWR}: LOS signals generally have higher channel power, as
  the direct path is unobstructed
\item
  \textbf{FP\_AMP1}: The first-path amplitude component is higher for
  LOS measurements
\item
  \textbf{STDEV\_NOISE}: NLOS environments tend to have more noise due
  to scattering
\end{itemize}

Features with significant distribution overlap (e.g., \texttt{RXPACC},
\texttt{FRAME\_LEN}) contribute less discriminative power, consistent
with the feature importance analysis.

\subsubsection{Plot 03: Pearson Correlation
Heatmap}\label{plot-03-pearson-correlation-heatmap}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={Pearson Correlation Matrix of Scalar Features}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/03_correlation_heatmap.png}}
\caption{Pearson Correlation Matrix of Scalar Features}
\end{figure}

The correlation matrix heatmap reveals linear relationships between all
scalar features. Notable patterns:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{FP\_AMP1, FP\_AMP2, FP\_AMP3} are highly correlated with each
  other (r \textgreater{} 0.9), indicating redundancy; these three
  features measure the same first-path signal at different receiver
  processing stages
\item
  \textbf{CIR\_PWR} is correlated with the FP\_AMP features, consistent
  with the physical relationship between path amplitude and total
  channel power
\item
  \textbf{STDEV\_NOISE and MAX\_NOISE} are highly correlated
  (\(r \approx 0.95\)), as both measure noise floor properties
\end{itemize}

High correlations suggest that dimensionality reduction (e.g., PCA)
could reduce the 11 scalar features further without significant
information loss. However, tree-based methods are robust to correlated
features, so all features are retained.

\subsubsection{Plot 04: CIR Examples with Detected
Paths}\label{plot-04-cir-examples-with-detected-paths}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={CIR Waveform Examples with Path 1 (triangle) and Path 2 (circle) Markers}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/04_cir_examples.png}}
\caption{CIR Waveform Examples with Path 1 (triangle) and Path 2
(circle) Markers}
\end{figure}

Four CIR waveform examples are plotted (two LOS and two NLOS), with the
detected Path 1 peak marked by an upward triangle and Path 2 by a
circle. This visualization directly illustrates the physical differences
motivating the entire project:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{LOS CIR}: A sharp, dominant first peak arrives at a low sample
  index with a steep rise and rapid decay. Path 2 (if detectable) is
  clearly separated and smaller in amplitude.
\item
  \textbf{NLOS CIR}: The first-arriving component is attenuated, and the
  CIR energy is spread across a wider temporal range. Multiple
  comparable-amplitude peaks may be visible, making Path 1 vs.~Path 2
  disambiguation harder.
\end{itemize}

The markers provide qualitative verification of the peak detection
algorithm: correctly placed triangles and circles are consistent with
the ±10-sample FP\_IDX refinement and the prominence-based Path 2
detection behavior on these examples.

\subsubsection{Plot 05: FP\_IDX Distribution by
Class}\label{plot-05-fp_idx-distribution-by-class}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={Distribution of First Path Index (FP\_IDX) by LOS/NLOS Class}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/05_fp_idx_distribution.png}}
\caption{Distribution of First Path Index (FP\_IDX) by LOS/NLOS Class}
\end{figure}

This histogram shows the distribution of the hardware-reported
first-path index (FP\_IDX) separately for LOS and NLOS measurements. LOS
measurements tend to have lower FP\_IDX values, corresponding to
earlier-arriving signals; the direct path travels the shortest possible
distance. NLOS measurements show a broader distribution shifted toward
higher FP\_IDX values, indicating that the first detected signal has
traveled a longer (reflected or diffracted) path.

The separation in FP\_IDX distributions suggests that it is a
discriminative feature, consistent with its high importance ranking in
the Random Forest analysis.

\subsubsection{Plot 06: Feature Importance (Random Forest
Gini)}\label{plot-06-feature-importance-random-forest-gini}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={Top 20 Feature Importances from Random Forest (Gini Impurity)}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/06_feature_importance.png}}
\caption{Top 20 Feature Importances from Random Forest (Gini Impurity)}
\end{figure}

Gini impurity-based feature importance ranks all 25 features by their
contribution to the forest's classification decisions. The top features
reveal which physical properties most distinguish LOS from NLOS:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{peak\_to\_noise}}: The ratio of peak amplitude to
  channel noise is the single most discriminative feature; LOS signals
  have substantially higher SNR
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{energy\_ratio}}: The fraction of CIR energy in the
  local peak window; LOS concentrates energy in the first path
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{CIR\_PWR}}: Total channel power; LOS paths typically
  deliver more energy to the receiver
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{path\_idx}} and \textbf{\texttt{FP\_IDX}}: Temporal
  position of the first path; earlier arrivals are more likely LOS
\item
  \textbf{\texttt{rms\_delay\_spread}}: NLOS environments produce
  broader, more spread-out multipath profiles
\end{itemize}

Lower-ranked features (\texttt{FRAME\_LEN}, \texttt{PREAM\_LEN}) are
protocol parameters with limited physical connection to propagation
conditions, confirming they contribute little.

\subsubsection{Plot 07: Confusion
Matrices}\label{plot-07-confusion-matrices}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={Confusion Matrices for Selected Inline Classification Models}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/07_confusion_matrices.png}}
\caption{Confusion Matrices for Selected Inline Classification Models}
\end{figure}

2×2 confusion matrices are shown for the inline tabular classifiers and
ensemble variants (Logistic Regression, SVM, Random Forest, GBT,
XGBoost, Ensemble Average, and Ensemble Stacked). Each matrix shows True
Positive (correctly predicted NLOS), True Negative (correctly predicted
LOS), False Positive (LOS predicted as NLOS), and False Negative (NLOS
predicted as LOS).

Key observations: - The strongest tree-based models and the ensemble
variants have similar confusion-matrix shapes, with false negatives
(missed NLOS detections) often slightly more common than false positives
- Logistic Regression produces a noticeably different error pattern,
with more symmetric but larger off-diagonal values - The low false
negative rate of tree-based models is particularly important for
positioning applications, where an undetected NLOS path causes larger
position errors than a false NLOS detection

\subsubsection{Plot 08: ROC Curves}\label{plot-08-roc-curves}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={ROC Curves for Inline Classification Models}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/08_roc_curves.png}}
\caption{ROC Curves for Inline Classification Models}
\end{figure}

Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curves plot the True Positive
Rate (sensitivity) against the False Positive Rate (1 - specificity) at
all possible classification thresholds. The Area Under the Curve (AUC)
summarizes overall classifier quality:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Logistic Regression}: AUC = 0.9730
\item
  \textbf{SVM (RBF)}: AUC = 0.9735
\item
  \textbf{Random Forest}: AUC = 0.9821
\item
  \textbf{Gradient Boosted Trees}: AUC = 0.9821
\item
  \textbf{XGBoost}: AUC = 0.9832
\item
  \textbf{Ensemble (Average)}: AUC = 0.9832
\item
  \textbf{Ensemble (Stacked)}: AUC = 0.9829
\end{itemize}

The ROC curves plot the inline tabular classifiers and ensembles only.
The separate raw-CIR CNN+Transformer result is competitive with the
strongest inline tabular models, but it is reported from a different
pipeline on the original split and is therefore summarized in Table 1
rather than overlaid here.

In this setup, AUC is a comparatively stable cross-model summary because
it is threshold-independent and less sensitive to differing class
balances. Even so, AUC does not fully remove the cross-pipeline
comparability caveat.

\subsubsection{Plot 09: Model Comparison (Accuracy and
AUC)}\label{plot-09-model-comparison-accuracy-and-auc}

\begin{figure}
