\subsubsection{Plot 10: Predicted vs.~Actual
Distance}\label{plot-10-predicted-vs.-actual-distance}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={Scatter Plots: Predicted vs.~Actual Range for Path 1 and Path 2}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/10_predicted_vs_actual.png}}
\caption{Scatter Plots: Predicted vs.~Actual Range for Path 1 and Path
2}
\end{figure}

Scatter plots compare the model's predicted range values (y-axis)
against the true range labels (x-axis) for both paths. A perfect
predictor would place all points on the diagonal line y = x.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Path 1}: The scatter plot shows moderate spread around the
  diagonal, reflecting the best test performance of roughly RMSE 1.37 m
  and R² 0.67. Larger deviations occur primarily in NLOS samples where
  the RANGE measurement itself includes a positive bias.
\item
  \textbf{Path 2}: Points are tightly concentrated around the diagonal,
  but this should not be overinterpreted as a pure learning success. The
  target definition is largely determined by supplied timing and RANGE
  terms, so the high R² values are partly built into the problem
  formulation.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Plot 11: Regression
Residuals}\label{plot-11-regression-residuals}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={Residual Distribution Plots for Path 1 and Path 2 Regression}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/11_residuals.png}}
\caption{Residual Distribution Plots for Path 1 and Path 2 Regression}
\end{figure}

Residual plots (predicted - actual) reveal systematic errors in the
regression models. Key observations:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Path 1 residuals}: Show a slight positive bias (model tends to
  underpredict range), most pronounced for large RANGE values. This
  reflects the NLOS bias in the training labels: for NLOS samples, the
  measured RANGE is systematically too large, but the model partially
  accounts for this.
\item
  \textbf{Path 2 residuals}: Tightly clustered around zero, consistent
  with the analytically constrained target construction. The few larger
  deviations correspond to cases where Path 2 timing is less reliably
  estimated.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Plot 12: Annotated CIR
Waveforms}\label{plot-12-annotated-cir-waveforms}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={CIR Waveforms with Detailed Feature Annotations}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/12_annotated_cir.png}}
\caption{CIR Waveforms with Detailed Feature Annotations}
\end{figure}

Selected CIR waveforms are annotated with computed feature values to
illustrate the connection between the raw waveform and the extracted
features. Annotations show:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  The rise\_time and decay\_time measurement windows around each path
  peak
\item
  The local kurtosis window (±15 samples)
\item
  The energy ratio measurement region
\item
  The path\_delay\_separation between Path 1 and Path 2
\item
  The 10\% amplitude threshold for rise/decay time computation
\end{itemize}

These annotations visually justify the feature engineering choices and
make the algorithm transparent to the reader.

\subsubsection{Plot 13: Transformer Attention
Maps}\label{plot-13-transformer-attention-maps}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={Transformer Attention Weights Overlaid on CIR Waveforms}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/13_attention_map.png}}
\caption{Transformer Attention Weights Overlaid on CIR Waveforms}
\end{figure}

For a subset of test samples, the first transformer layer's attention
weights are extracted and overlaid as a heatmap on the corresponding CIR
waveform. High attention values (bright regions) indicate which temporal
positions the model considers most informative for its classification
decision.

Key observation: the attention maps often show elevated attention near
the first path peak and near later multipath components. This pattern is
qualitatively consistent with physically meaningful CIR regions, so the
plots are best treated as interpretability cues rather than as
definitive explanations of model behavior.

\subsubsection{Plot 14: K-Means Clustering on Expanded Two-Path
Features}\label{plot-14-k-means-clustering-on-expanded-two-path-features}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={PCA Scatter of K-Means Clusters and True Labels on Expanded Two-Path Features}]{/Users/cantabile/projects/sit/csc3105/csc3105-project/plots/14_clustering.png}}
\caption{PCA Scatter of K-Means Clusters and True Labels on Expanded
Two-Path Features}
\end{figure}

This side-by-side PCA scatter plot compares the \textbf{K-Means cluster
assignments} and the \textbf{true LOS/NLOS labels} for the expanded
two-path feature set used in the clustering experiment. The
visualization shows substantial overlap between the learned groups and
the true classes. This is consistent with the quantitative clustering
results (accuracy 0.5700, ARI -0.0099): the engineered features are
useful for supervised learning, but they do \textbf{not} yield strong
unsupervised recovery of LOS/NLOS structure under the tested clustering
settings.

