Ensemble (Average) & 0.9399 & 0.9832 & Expanded 2-path set \\
Ensemble (Stacked) & 0.9413 & 0.9829 & Expanded 2-path set \\
CNN+Transformer & 0.9368 & 0.9827 & Original-split raw-CIR pipeline \\
CNN+Transformer + Augmentation & 0.9387 & 0.9862 & Original-split
raw-CIR pipeline \\
\end{longtable}
}

\paragraph{Key Finding: Strong ML Baseline, Competitive DL
Result}\label{key-finding-strong-ml-baseline-competitive-dl-result}

Within the inline notebook benchmark, tree-based tabular models remain
very strong: XGBoost achieves the best single-model AUC (0.9832), and
the stacked ensemble achieves the best inline accuracy (0.9413).

The separate raw-CIR CNN+Transformer result is competitive, and its
augmented version slightly exceeds the best inline AUC numerically.
Because the deep-learning figures are pre-computed from a different
workflow, this is interpreted as \textbf{cross-pipeline
competitiveness}, not definitive parity or superiority in a single
controlled benchmark.

\paragraph{Logistic Regression Suggests
Non-Linearity}\label{logistic-regression-suggests-non-linearity}

The lower Logistic Regression AUC (0.9730 vs.~0.9832 for the best inline
XGBoost model) suggests that the LOS/NLOS decision boundary in
25-dimensional feature space is genuinely non-linear. This gap justifies
the use of stronger non-linear learners.

\paragraph{Fair-Comparison Context}\label{fair-comparison-context}

A rigorous architecture comparison would require all model families to
be trained and evaluated on an identical sample definition, split
protocol, and preprocessing flow. Because the tabular and deep results
here come from different reporting pipelines, this report uses AUC and
directionally consistent trends as the main cross-model lens and treats
raw-accuracy differences cautiously.

\paragraph{Synthetic Data Impact}\label{synthetic-data-impact}

\textbf{SMOTE + Random Forest}: The effect is negligible. The notebook
reports \textbf{RF + SMOTE = 0.9395 / 0.9816} versus \textbf{RF original
= 0.9396 / 0.9821}, so oversampling does not materially improve the
already large tabular training set.

\textbf{CIR Augmentation + CNN+Transformer}: In the separate
pre-computed raw-CIR pipeline, augmentation shifts the CNN+Transformer
from \textbf{0.9368 / 0.9827} to \textbf{0.9387 / 0.9862}. Accuracy
moves only marginally (+0.0019) while AUC improves more meaningfully
(+0.0035), indicating that augmentation primarily sharpens the model's
ranking/calibration rather than its top-1 decisions. This is still a
more noticeable gain than the SMOTE result, but it should be discussed
as a cross-pipeline augmentation study rather than as an inline notebook
retraining experiment.

Conclusion: augmentation effects are representation-dependent in this
project. SMOTE is largely redundant for the tabular pipeline, whereas
waveform-level augmentation appears more helpful for the separate
raw-CIR deep model.

